Too many restaurants, too little room in my pants.
Although on my list, Fogo De Chao had taken a back seat to other less deserving establishments it seems.
Not forgotten, just cast aside for the time being.
I hang my head in shame at that now.
I could not resist the abundance of tempting offerings at the salad bar.
Since I could not possibly try everything and still eat meat, I opted to sacrifice everything green.
I filled my plate with cheeses, smoked salmon, prosciutto, roasted veggies, and everything not in the leafy green category.
At the table, I could also not resist the fried polenta and fried bananas.
And those little popovers!
Since they were small, I didn't count how many I consumed.
Leaving little room for the meat attraction, what I did sample was tender and flavorful.
Big thanks to Gabi and the wonderful staff in the front and in the kitchen who made sure we were taken care of from start to finish.
Once I recover, I'll be back for more!

I have been to four such places in the Phoenix area and if you combine food and ambience this is the best by a mile.
The service was exceptional--we didn't have to wait for anything and people were coming by constantly not only to serve us a gajillion types of meat, but to check on our every need.
Refills?
Sauces?
A particular cut you'd like?
Anything and everything was available right away.
We got taken on a tour of the kitchen and it is huge and spotless.
There is also a private room which apparently is first-come-first-served and is no additional charge.
There is a salad bar with chilled asparagus, hearts of palm, and the most ridiculous artichoke hearts--literally just the very best part of the artichoke here.
There was a delicious chicken salad, potato salad, a bunch of cheeses, and cold cuts.
But of course, the main event was the meat--sausage, sirloin, leg of lamb, chicken legs, bacon wrapped chicken breast, bacon wrapped filet... and the best cut of filet mignon that I've had in a long time.
Tender, amazing, delightful.
This place also gets extra kudos for the fact that the servers ask as they are cutting the meat which doneness you want, which is nice.
I really enjoyed it.
Finally--the dessert was sublime.
Between the three of us, we shared the papaya-ice cream-black currant liqueur thingy, which wasn't too sweet but wonderfully subtle; the molten chocolate cake which would be the most perfect desert known to humanity if it had a few more fresh berries on there, and a wonderful creme brulee which capped off my birthday in the best possible way.
Gabi was evasive when I asked if it was her who ratted me out and scored me a free birthday dessert but I will go ahead and give her the credit since she's just so all-around exceptional.
Once again, an exceptional event--thanks to Yelp and most importantly, thanks so much to Fogo de Chao.

